Here are the **top 5 summarized points** you can use in a presentation about the **disadvantages of GitHub Copilot Instruction and Skill files**. These are simplified and presentation-friendly.

---

## 1️⃣ Not Strictly Enforced

Copilot instruction and skill files only **guide code generation**, but they **cannot enforce coding standards**. Developers must still rely on tools like **Checkstyle, SonarQube, and code reviews**.

---

## 2️⃣ Limited Context Understanding

Copilot cannot fully understand **system architecture, business logic, or project structure**, so generated code may **violate architectural patterns or design principles**.

---

## 3️⃣ Inconsistent Behavior

Copilot may **ignore parts of instruction or skill files**, especially when files are large, leading to **inconsistent or mixed coding styles**.

---

## 4️⃣ Maintenance Overhead

Instruction and skill files must be **continuously updated** as technologies, frameworks, and coding standards evolve, otherwise they can become **outdated or misleading**.

---

## 5️⃣ Potential Security and Governance Risks

These files may expose **internal practices, architecture details, or workflows**, and without governance they can become **difficult to manage across multiple repositories or teams**.

---

✅ **One-line takeaway for presentations**

> Copilot instruction and skill files improve developer productivity, but they **do not replace code quality tools, architectural governance, or proper code reviews**.

